#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
MKT Christ — Amos chapters 6–9 (ch 9:11 already present, skipped by merge)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-amos-6-9-full.py

Key Christological connections:
- 6:1 woe to complacent → Luke 6:24-25 (woe to the rich/full — same prophetic form)
- 6:4-6 luxury while Joseph ruins → Luke 16:19-31 (rich man and Lazarus)
- 7:1-6 intercession averts judgment → Heb 7:25 (Christ intercedes)
- 7:10-17 institutional opposition to prophet → Matt 21:23-27 (chief priests vs Jesus)
- 8:9 sun dark at noon → Luke 23:44 (crucifixion darkness — direct echo)
- 8:10 mourning for an only son → John 3:16 (God's only begotten)
- 8:11 famine of the word → John 1:14 (Word became flesh); John 6:35
- 9:9 sifted like wheat → Luke 22:31-32 (Satan sifts, Jesus intercedes)
- 9:13 new wine from mountains → John 2:1-11 (Cana as eschatological sign)
"""

import json
from pathlib import Path

ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

AMOS = {
    "6": {
        "1": '<p class="christ-allusion">The woe-oracle against those who are complacent in Zion is taken up in identical form by Jesus: the Lucan beatitudes reverse into woes directed at the self-satisfied — &quot;Woe to you who are rich, for you have received your consolation&quot; (Luke 6:24). The prophetic woe-form runs directly from Amos through Jesus. What Amos pronounces over the Samarian elite, Jesus pronounces over any who find their sufficiency in present comfort rather than the kingdom. The form of judgment-speech is constant; only the audience changes.</p>',
        "2": '<p class="christ-theme">The call to survey fallen Calneh, Hamath, and Gath establishes the governing principle of the woes: no one is exempt from judgment based on status or past greatness. Jesus reiterates this principle when he points to Galileans whose blood Pilate mingled with sacrifices and the eighteen killed by the tower of Siloam: &quot;unless you repent, you will all likewise perish&quot; (Luke 13:1-5). No tragedy is punishment for uniquely bad sinners; all alike stand before the same Judge.</p>',
        "3": '<p class="christ-theme">Those who &quot;put off the day of disaster&quot; while drawing violence near embody the eschatological blindness Jesus addresses in his parables of watchfulness: the servant who says &quot;my master is delayed&quot; and begins to eat and drink with drunkards (Matt 24:48-49). The pattern is structural — those who suppress awareness of coming judgment accelerate the very conditions they deny. Both Amos and Jesus call for sober reckoning with the nearness of the day.</p>',
        "4": '<p class="christ-type">The portrait of the elite lying on ivory beds, sprawling on couches, eating choice animals — while unable to grieve the ruin around them — is the OT type that Jesus crystallizes in the parable of the Rich Man and Lazarus (Luke 16:19-31). The rich man dressed in purple and fine linen and feasted sumptuously every day while Lazarus lay at his gate. Both texts locate the sin not in luxury per se but in the absence of grief over those perishing nearby. The type reaches its antitype in the one who &quot;had nowhere to lay his head&quot; (Matt 8:20) yet was moved with compassion for every crowd.</p>',
        "5": '<p class="christ-theme">The irony of improvising songs &quot;like David&quot; while living opposite to David&apos;s orientation is not lost on Jesus, who repeatedly invokes David as an example of one who served God&apos;s purposes under constraint, not abundance (Matt 12:3-4 — David eating the showbread; Mark 12:35-37 — David&apos;s son as David&apos;s lord). The contrast Amos draws between self-serving music and David&apos;s covenantal music anticipates the distinction Jesus draws between religious performance and genuine orientation toward God.</p>',
        "6": '<p class="christ-allusion">Drinking from sacrificial bowls (<em>mizraqim</em>) and &quot;not being grieved over the ruin of Joseph&quot; — the anesthesia of luxury against covenant responsibility — is the condition Jesus describes as the rich man&apos;s failure (Luke 16:24-31). Even after death, the rich man cannot comprehend why his condition is what it is. Amos identifies the root: the inability to grieve the ruin of others while one&apos;s own comfort is secured. Christologically, the one who &quot;grieves over the ruin of Joseph&quot; is Christ himself — the Man of Sorrows acquainted with grief (Isa 53:3) who weeps over Jerusalem (Luke 19:41).</p>',
        "7": '<p class="christ-allusion">The irony of the &quot;first of the nations&quot; becoming &quot;first to go into exile&quot; echoes Jesus&apos;s principle that &quot;the first shall be last and the last first&quot; (Matt 19:30; 20:16). The kingdom calculus is the structural inversion of the world&apos;s ranking. What Amos announces as judgment — the elevated brought low — Jesus announces as kingdom logic: the one who humbles himself will be exalted, and the exalted humbled (Luke 18:14). Christ himself enacts the deepest form of this: the one who was first becomes last through crucifixion, and through resurrection becomes first in a new order entirely.</p>',
        "8": '<p class="christ-allusion">YHWH swearing &quot;by himself&quot; (<em>bi-nafshō</em>) establishes the self-authenticating character of the divine oath. Hebrews 6:13-17 reflects on this directly: &quot;when God made a promise to Abraham, since he had no one greater by whom to swear, he swore by himself.&quot; The divine oath as the ground of certainty — an oath confirmed by God&apos;s own nature — is the basis of the hope offered in Christ, who is &quot;the guarantor of a better covenant&quot; (Heb 7:22). What YHWH swears in Amos is judgment; what YHWH swears in Hebrews is the promise of salvation. Same oath-logic, different content.</p>',
        "9": '<p class="christ-theme">The scenario of ten remaining in a house who all die depicts the completeness of judgment — no remnant survives the complacent elite&apos;s household. The reversal of this image appears in Jesus&apos;s parables of recovery: the woman who searches her whole house for the one lost coin (Luke 15:8-9). The logic is opposite: judgment leaves no one standing; grace leaves no one behind. Christ comes as the searcher who will not rest until the lost is found.</p>',
        "10": '<p class="christ-theme">The terror of invoking the divine name — &quot;we must not mention the name of YHWH&quot; — in the context of judgment reflects the reversal of the blessing-function of the divine name. The name invoked for protection becomes too dangerous to speak. Jesus restores the name to its blessing-function: &quot;Whatever you ask in my name, this I will do&quot; (John 14:13). The holy name, which in Amos&apos;s judgment-context becomes too terrible to invoke, in Christ becomes the name by which prayer is heard — because the judgment the name represents has been absorbed by the one who bears it.</p>',
        "11": '<p class="christ-theme">The great house struck to rubble and the small house to splinters signals that the judgment makes no exemptions based on wealth or scale. Jesus teaches the same principle in the Sermon on the Mount: the house built on sand falls when the storm comes, regardless of how impressive the structure was (Matt 7:26-27). The only foundation that survives judgment is the one built on Christ&apos;s words — the rock on which the wise builder constructs his house (Matt 7:24-25).</p>',
        "12": '<p class="christ-theme">The rhetorical questions about logical impossibility — horses on rock, oxen plowing the sea — are the OT form of what Jesus states directly: a house divided against itself cannot stand (Mark 3:25). Turning justice to poison violates the same rational structure as the impossible images. Jesus likewise uses the logic of self-contradiction to expose the bankruptcy of his opponents&apos; positions (Matt 12:25-26). Both operate with the assumption that moral reality has a rational structure that corruption ultimately violates.</p>',
        "13": '<p class="christ-allusion">Rejoicing in &quot;Lo-dabar&quot; (nothing) and taking credit for military strength they did not generate through their own faithfulness anticipates the parable of the servant who says &quot;my master is delayed&quot; and asserts his own authority (Luke 12:45). The self-congratulatory claim — &quot;did we not capture Karnaim by our own strength?&quot; — is the attitude Jesus addresses in the parable of the Pharisee who prays &quot;God, I thank you that I am not like other men&quot; (Luke 18:11). Boasting in &quot;nothing&quot; is the spiritual condition that disqualifies from grace.</p>',
        "14": '<p class="christ-theme">YHWH raising up a nation to oppress Israel from Hamath to the Arabah — the instrument of judgment — prefigures the pattern Christ describes as the judgment falling on Jerusalem through Rome (Luke 21:20-24). Both texts use historical military power as the instrument of divine judgment on covenant-breaking communities. The theological principle is consistent: YHWH works through historical agents to execute his purposes, whether judgment or redemption, without that agency entailing the agent&apos;s innocence.</p>'
    },
    "7": {
        "1": '<p class="christ-type">The first vision of locust-judgment poised and then averted through intercession is a type of Christ&apos;s high-priestly intercession. Amos stands between YHWH&apos;s judgment and a helpless people and appeals to covenant mercy: &quot;O Lord YHWH, please forgive — how can Jacob stand? He is so small!&quot; The intercession is effective — YHWH relents. This intercession-pattern anticipates Christ, who &quot;always lives to make intercession for them&quot; (Heb 7:25) — not averting judgment, but having absorbed it, interceding from within the covenant on behalf of those who are &quot;so small.&quot;</p>',
        "2": '<p class="christ-allusion">The appeal to smallness — &quot;how can Jacob stand? He is so small!&quot; — as the ground for intercession rather than any claim to merit anticipates Paul&apos;s principle that &quot;God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong&quot; (1 Cor 1:27). The effective intercession rests not on Jacob&apos;s size but on YHWH&apos;s character. Christ&apos;s intercession rests on the same ground — not on the merit of those for whom he intercedes but on the Father&apos;s own commitment to the covenant sealed in his Son&apos;s blood (Heb 9:15).</p>',
        "3": '<p class="christ-type">YHWH &quot;relenting&quot; (<em>nacham</em>) in response to prophetic intercession is the OT pattern for what Christ makes permanent. The relenting is provisional in Amos — it happens twice and then is withdrawn. In Christ, the relenting is made stable: God &quot;was reconciling the world to himself in Christ, not counting their trespasses against them&quot; (2 Cor 5:19). The provisional &quot;it shall not be&quot; of prophetic intercession becomes the permanent &quot;no condemnation&quot; (Rom 8:1) secured through the Son&apos;s own standing in the Father&apos;s presence.</p>',
        "4": '<p class="christ-type">The fire-vision consuming the great deep and the land escalates the first vision: cosmic-scale destruction poised. The pattern of judgment withheld through intercession reaches its limit in these visions. Christ bears the fire that would have consumed — &quot;our God is a consuming fire&quot; (Heb 12:29) — absorbing in himself the penalty that judgment-fire represents. The fire that consumed Sodom, that threatened Israel in Amos&apos;s visions, falls on the Son at the cross: &quot;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&quot; (Gal 3:13).</p>',
        "5": '<p class="christ-type">Amos&apos;s second intercession — &quot;O Lord YHWH, please stop (<em>chadal</em>)&quot; — uses a different verb, perhaps reflecting the urgency of cosmic threat. The shift mirrors Christ&apos;s Gethsemane prayer: &quot;Father, if it is possible, let this cup pass from me; nevertheless, not as I will, but as you will&quot; (Matt 26:39). Both intercessors appeal urgently for the judgment to stop. The difference: Amos&apos;s appeal succeeds in the short term; Christ&apos;s appeal is answered through resurrection, not avoidance — the cup is drunk so that the judgment-fire is extinguished for all who are in him.</p>',
        "6": '<p class="christ-type">The second divine relenting closes the intercession-pattern before the pivot to the plumb line. The two relentings establish YHWH&apos;s genuine responsiveness to intercession and heighten the significance of what follows. Christologically, the relentings model the intercessory office that Christ fulfills permanently — except that Christ&apos;s intercession is based not on the smallness and vulnerability of God&apos;s people (Amos&apos;s appeal) but on his own blood and resurrection (Heb 7:25; Rom 8:34). The response is not provisional relenting but definitive justification.</p>',
        "7": '<p class="christ-allusion">The plumb line (<em>anakh</em>) measures Israel against the standard of its own building. Christ is himself the standard against which the human project is measured — &quot;the stone that the builders rejected has become the cornerstone&quot; (Matt 21:42). The measuring that Amos sees in vision is the measuring that Revelation makes explicit: the angel with a measuring rod measuring the temple and city (Rev 21:15-17). What the plumb line reveals in Amos is that Israel has deviated; what Christ reveals is the standard by which all deviation is exposed and all that is built on him is found true.</p>',
        "8": '<p class="christ-allusion">The divine declaration &quot;I will never again pass over them&quot; — closing the intercession-era — is the covenant announcement that the long patience of judgment-averted has ended. In Christ, the counterpart is not the end of mercy but the end of the old covenant&apos;s provisional arrangements: &quot;in these last days he has spoken to us by his Son&quot; (Heb 1:2). The plumb line placed in Israel&apos;s midst is the standard that Christ fulfills perfectly and that reveals all human falling-short. He is simultaneously the measurer and the standard against which all are measured.</p>',
        "9": '<p class="christ-allusion">The desolation of the high places of Isaac and the sanctuaries of Israel anticipates Jesus&apos;s own announcement regarding the temple: &quot;not one stone here will be left on another&quot; (Matt 24:2). Both prophetic declarations arise from the same logic — the sanctuary that has become a tool of human self-serving rather than a place of genuine covenant encounter will be removed. Jesus himself replaces the temple as the dwelling of God with humanity (John 2:19-21), rendering the physical destruction of the old sanctuary the precondition for the new.</p>',
        "10": '<p class="christ-type">Amaziah the priest reporting Amos&apos;s message to Jeroboam as conspiracy prefigures the religious-political alliance that delivered Jesus to Pilate. The chief priests report to Caesar: &quot;if you release this man, you are not Caesar&apos;s friend&quot; (John 19:12). Both scenes involve religious leaders using the political authority of the throne against an unauthorized prophetic voice. Both frame prophetic proclamation as political subversion. The pattern — established messenger vs. institutional religion aligned with state power — runs from Amos through the passion narrative.</p>',
        "11": '<p class="christ-allusion">Amaziah&apos;s report that &quot;the land is not able to bear all his words&quot; anticipates the same charge against Jesus: &quot;this is the heir; come, let us kill him and have his inheritance&quot; (Matt 21:38). The institutional response to prophetic speech that challenges the existing order is suppression. In both cases, the one suppressed is vindicated — Amos&apos;s words are fulfilled in Israel&apos;s exile; Jesus is vindicated by resurrection. The words the land cannot bear become the words the earth cannot contain (John 21:25).</p>',
        "12": '<p class="christ-allusion">Amaziah&apos;s command — go to Judah, prophesy there for bread — assumes that prophetic speech is a professional service rendered for economic compensation. Jesus addresses this assumption in sending the disciples: &quot;take no gold or silver or copper in your belts&quot; (Matt 10:9). The apostolic mission is not a professional service but a prophetic commission. The charge that Amos (or Jesus) prophesied for commercial gain misses the divine origin of the commission entirely.</p>',
        "13": '<p class="christ-allusion">Bethel as &quot;the king&apos;s sanctuary and royal house&quot; — the institutional alignment of sacred space with political power — is exactly what Jesus challenges in the temple cleansing (Matt 21:12-13): &quot;my house shall be called a house of prayer, but you have made it a den of thieves.&quot; Both Amos and Jesus confront the same structural problem: the space designated for divine-human encounter has been captured by institutional and economic interests. Both acts of confrontation lead directly to the authorities plotting the prophet&apos;s removal.</p>',
        "14": '<p class="christ-allusion">Amos&apos;s disclaimer — &quot;I am not a prophet (<em>lo navi anoki</em>) nor a prophet&apos;s son&quot; — is echoed in John the Baptist&apos;s denial: &quot;I am not the Christ... not Elijah... not the Prophet&quot; (John 1:20-21). Both figures disclaim institutional prophetic identity while asserting divine commission. Amos was &quot;taken&quot; from the flock by YHWH; Jesus declares &quot;the Father who sent me has himself given me a commandment&quot; (John 12:49). Authority in both cases derives from divine commission, not prophetic office.</p>',
        "15": '<p class="christ-allusion">YHWH took Amos from following the flock and said &quot;Go, prophesy to my people Israel.&quot; The pattern of divine seizure creating prophetic commission — from unexpected, non-institutional origins — is the model for the apostolic call: &quot;as he walked by the Sea of Galilee, he saw Simon and Andrew casting their net... and Jesus said, &apos;Follow me&apos;&quot; (Mark 1:16-17). Fishermen, tax collectors, shepherds — the pattern of calling from ordinary labor into prophetic commission runs from Amos through the Twelve. The commission is always divine, never self-appointed.</p>',
        "16": '<p class="christ-theme">The command &quot;Now hear the word of YHWH&quot; turned back against Amaziah who tried to silence it establishes the irresistibility of prophetic speech. Jesus asserts the same: &quot;heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will not pass away&quot; (Matt 24:35). The word that institutional power tries to suppress returns as judgment on the one who suppressed it. In both Amos and Jesus, the attempt to silence is the trigger for its amplification — the very act of suppression ensures the word&apos;s continuation.</p>',
        "17": '<p class="christ-type">The specific judgment on Amaziah — wife dishonored, children killed, land divided, exile on unclean soil — inverts the priestly blessing he would have presumed to bestow. Amos is the priest&apos;s judge rather than his suppliant. Christ stands in this same relation to the religious establishment: &quot;the Son of Man will send his angels, and they will gather... all causes of sin and all law-breakers&quot; (Matt 13:41). The judgment Amos pronounces on the priest who silenced him is a type of the judgment Christ pronounces on institutional religion that has become a barrier to rather than mediator of the divine presence.</p>'
    },
    "8": {
        "1": '<p class="christ-allusion">The basket of summer fruit (<em>kayits</em>) announces the end (<em>qetz</em>) through a visual pun. The nearness of harvest and termination simultaneously — the moment of apparent fullness is the moment of ending — anticipates Jesus&apos;s eschatological language: &quot;when the branch becomes tender and puts out its leaves, you know that summer is near&quot; (Matt 24:32). The fig tree&apos;s budding is a sign of the end&apos;s nearness. In both Amos and Jesus, the imagery of natural ripeness encodes eschatological terminus.</p>',
        "2": '<p class="christ-direct">The end has come upon Israel — YHWH will &quot;never again pass over them.&quot; The declaration parallels Jesus&apos;s announcement of judgment on the temple generation: &quot;this generation will not pass away until all these things take place&quot; (Matt 24:34). The termination Amos announces for the Northern Kingdom in 722 BCE is the pattern for the termination Jesus announces for the Jerusalem that rejected him in 70 CE. Both judgments are expressions of the same covenant logic: the patience of YHWH exhausted, the end arrived.</p>',
        "3": '<p class="christ-allusion">Songs turned to wailing, the many corpses, the terrible silence — this image anticipates the eschatological reversal Jesus describes at the wedding banquet parable&apos;s close: those not properly clothed are cast out into outer darkness &quot;where there is weeping and gnashing of teeth&quot; (Matt 22:13). The feast that should have been joy becomes grief for those who treated the invitation lightly. The silence Amos describes — no one daring even to speak YHWH&apos;s name — is the silence of complete covenant collapse.</p>',
        "4": '<p class="christ-allusion">Those who trample the needy and destroy the poor are the objects of Jesus&apos;s most urgent warnings: &quot;Whoever causes one of these little ones who believe in me to sin, it would be better for him to have a great millstone fastened around his neck and to be drowned&quot; (Matt 18:6). The systematic economic exploitation Amos indicts is the exact condition James denounces using the same prophetic logic (Jas 5:1-6): the wages withheld from laborers cry out; the rich have lived on earth in luxury and self-indulgence. The prophetic stream from Amos to James is direct.</p>',
        "5": '<p class="christ-allusion">Falsified weights and measures — the ephah made small, the shekel inflated, the scales deceitful — are the economic instruments of the exploitation Jesus exposes in his parable of the dishonest steward and his teaching that &quot;you cannot serve God and money&quot; (Matt 6:24). The entire commercial infrastructure being corrupt from within is the material counterpart to the spiritual corruption of the Pharisees whose &quot;inside of the cup&quot; is full of greed and self-indulgence (Matt 23:25). Christ exposes the inner corruption the external apparatus conceals.</p>',
        "6": '<p class="christ-allusion">Buying the poor for silver and the needy for a pair of sandals — debt slavery — reaches its NT application in James&apos;s direct use of Amos&apos;s imagery: &quot;the wages of the laborers who mowed your fields, which you kept back by fraud, are crying out against you&quot; (Jas 5:4). More profoundly, the selling of the innocent for silver prefigures Judas selling Jesus for thirty pieces: the righteous one traded as a commodity (Matt 26:15). Amos&apos;s covenant indictment and the passion narrative share a structural pattern.</p>',
        "7": '<p class="christ-theme">YHWH&apos;s oath never to forget their deeds — the certainty of divine memory and eventual judgment — is the ground of both warning and hope in the NT. Warning: &quot;God is not mocked; whatever one sows, that will he also reap&quot; (Gal 6:7). Hope: God&apos;s memory also works in favor of the righteous — &quot;God is not unjust so as to forget your work and love&quot; (Heb 6:10). The divine memory that Amos deploys as a judgment-guarantee becomes in Christ the guarantee of reward for covenant faithfulness.</p>',
        "8": '<p class="christ-theme">The earth&apos;s trembling and rising like the Nile at divine judgment anticipates the cosmic signs at the crucifixion: &quot;the earth shook, and the rocks were split&quot; (Matt 27:51) and the resurrection: &quot;there was a great earthquake&quot; (Matt 28:2). The cosmic disturbance Amos envisions as the earth&apos;s response to covenant injustice reaches its most concentrated expression when the author of the covenant is executed on a cross. Creation itself registers the event as the cosmic judgment-event that Amos&apos;s earthquake imagery anticipates.</p>',
        "9": '<p class="christ-allusion">The sun going dark at noon — &quot;I will darken the earth on a bright day&quot; — is fulfilled at the crucifixion: &quot;there was darkness over all the land until the ninth hour&quot; (Luke 23:44; Matt 27:45). The solar eclipse that Amos envisions as the Day of the LORD arriving finds its most literal-yet-symbolic enactment when the Son is crucified at midday and the sky goes dark until 3pm. The darkness signals divine judgment and cosmic mourning simultaneously — the creation&apos;s response to the death of its creator.</p>',
        "10": '<p class="christ-allusion">The mourning &quot;as for an only son&quot; (<em>ke-misped al-yachid</em>) is one of the OT&apos;s most intense grief-images. Zechariah 12:10 uses the same image for Israel mourning the one they have pierced: &quot;they will mourn for him as one mourns for an only child.&quot; John 19:37 cites Zechariah 12:10 for the crucifixion. The chain is explicit: Amos&apos;s mourning-for-an-only-son image is taken up by Zechariah for the pierced one, and fulfilled in the mourning at the cross. God&apos;s own mourning for his only Son (John 3:16) is the ultimate enactment of this image.</p>',
        "11": '<p class="christ-allusion">The famine of hearing the words of YHWH — not bread or water but the divine word withheld — finds its antithesis in Christ, who is himself the Word made flesh (John 1:14). Jesus declares himself the end of this famine: &quot;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me shall not hunger, and whoever believes in me shall never thirst&quot; (John 6:35). The word-famine Amos announces as judgment is the negative space that Christ fills positively. His presence in the world is the answer to the famine; his absence (John 7:34) restores the famine for those who reject him.</p>',
        "12": '<p class="christ-allusion">Wandering from sea to sea seeking the word of YHWH and not finding it echoes Jesus&apos;s announcement: &quot;you will seek me and you will not find me&quot; (John 7:34), addressed to those who reject him. The word-famine Amos threatens for covenant-breakers is the condition Jesus describes for those who let the moment of visitation pass. Conversely, those who do seek find: &quot;seek and you will find; knock and it will be opened&quot; (Matt 7:7). The seeking Amos describes ends in nothing; the seeking Jesus commissions ends in the One who is himself the sought word.</p>',
        "13": '<p class="christ-theme">Young women and young men fainting from thirst for the word is the image of the word-famine at its most devastating — those with the most vitality are the most enfeebled by its absence. Christ addresses this in the Sermon on the Mount: &quot;blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be satisfied&quot; (Matt 5:6). The thirst Amos describes ending in nothing, Jesus describes as the opening condition for satisfaction. The beatitude reverses the curse: the very thirst that Amos presents as evidence of abandonment, Jesus presents as the posture that receives fullness.</p>',
        "14": '<p class="christ-theme">Those who swear by false objects of devotion — the shame of Samaria, the way of Beersheba — and fall and do not rise foreshadow Jesus&apos;s warning that no one can serve two masters (Matt 6:24). The specific named objects of false loyalty (a deity, a pilgrimage route) represent the diffusion of covenantal commitment that disqualifies from covenantal life. &quot;They shall fall, and never rise again&quot; is the judgment on those whose ultimate loyalty is placed anywhere other than YHWH — the condition Christ identifies as the one form of loss that is permanent (Luke 9:25).</p>'
    },
    "9": {
        "1": '<p class="christ-allusion">YHWH standing at the altar commanding its destruction — sanctuary judgment — reaches its NT climax when Jesus declares the temple&apos;s desolation (Matt 24:2) and when Stephen sees the Son of Man standing at the right hand of God while the temple establishment moves to stone him (Acts 7:56). The sanctuary is not destroyed arbitrarily but because the covenantal reality it pointed to has arrived — Christ himself is the true temple (John 2:21), making the physical structure obsolete.</p>',
        "2": '<p class="christ-theme">The escape-impossibility litany — Sheol to heaven, Carmel to sea — establishes that divine judgment is inescapable. The NT counterpart is Paul&apos;s declaration of its positive reverse: nothing &quot;will be able to separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus our Lord&quot; (Rom 8:38-39). The same cosmic omnipresence deployed in Amos for judgment-inescapability is deployed in Romans for salvation-inescapability. The God from whom there is no hiding in judgment is the God from whom there is no exile in love.</p>',
        "3": '<p class="christ-theme">Even on Carmel&apos;s summit, in the sea&apos;s depths, the divine hand reaches. Hebrews 4:13 restates this for the eschatological judgment: &quot;no creature is hidden from his sight, but all are naked and exposed to the eyes of him to whom we must give account.&quot; The same nakedness before divine sight that is terror in Amos becomes in Hebrews the ground for approaching &quot;with confidence to the throne of grace&quot; (Heb 4:16) — because the judge is also the great high priest who sympathizes with our weakness.</p>',
        "4": '<p class="christ-theme">Even captivity before enemies does not constitute escape — YHWH commands the sword there. The inescapability of divine judgment is the premise for the urgency of the gospel: &quot;it is appointed for man to die once, and after that comes judgment&quot; (Heb 9:27). But the same logic that makes judgment inescapable makes redemption total: if YHWH&apos;s reach extends to every corner of the cosmos in judgment, it extends equally in salvation for those in Christ. The God who commands the sword there is the God who commands the angel &quot;do not harm those who have the seal of God&quot; (Rev 9:4).</p>',
        "5": '<p class="christ-theme">The doxology — YHWH who touches the earth and it melts, who builds his upper chambers in the heavens — grounds the judgment in the character of the Creator. Paul applies the same ground-of-creation logic to Christ: &quot;all things were created through him and for him... and in him all things hold together&quot; (Col 1:16-17). The one whose touch makes the earth melt is the one whose incarnation sustains its existence. The judge of the cosmos is its creator — the same power that melts the earth in judgment rebuilds it in new creation.</p>',
        "6": '<p class="christ-theme">The cosmic architect who builds his upper chambers in the heavens and calls for the waters of the sea is identified in the NT as the pre-existent Son through whom all things were made (John 1:3; Heb 1:2-3). &quot;YHWH is his name&quot; — the divine name that closes the doxology — is the name that Philippians 2:9-11 applies to the exalted Christ: &quot;the name that is above every name, that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow.&quot; The creator-judge of Amos&apos;s doxology is identified in the NT as the incarnate Son.</p>',
        "7": '<p class="christ-direct">The challenge to Israel&apos;s election-privilege — &quot;Are you not like the Cushites to me?&quot; — establishes a universalism that Acts and Paul develop directly. Peter declares at Cornelius&apos;s household: &quot;I truly understand that God shows no partiality, but in every nation anyone who fears him and does what is right is acceptable to him&quot; (Acts 10:34-35). Paul: &quot;There is neither Jew nor Greek... for you are all one in Christ Jesus&quot; (Gal 3:28). Amos&apos;s challenge is the OT seed of the NT&apos;s Gentile mission — election creates obligation, not superiority, and God&apos;s sovereign freedom extends to all nations.</p>',
        "8": '<p class="christ-allusion">The tension between destroying the sinful kingdom and not utterly destroying the house of Jacob is the OT form of Paul&apos;s argument in Romans 9-11. The &quot;not utterly&quot; is the remnant theology: &quot;at the present time there is a remnant, chosen by grace&quot; (Rom 11:5). The distinction Amos makes between the corporate political entity (destroyed) and the covenant community (preserved through remnant) is the distinction Paul makes between Israel according to the flesh and Israel according to the promise. Christ is the one in whom the remnant is identified and preserved.</p>',
        "9": '<p class="christ-allusion">The sifting of Israel among the nations like grain in a sieve — &quot;not one pebble shall fall to the earth&quot; — is the image Jesus directly applies to the disciples: &quot;Simon, Simon, Satan has demanded to sift you like wheat, but I have prayed for you that your faith may not fail&quot; (Luke 22:31-32). The sifting that Amos envisions as the mechanism of judgment becomes in Jesus&apos;s intercession the crucible of purification. Christ&apos;s prayer is the specific form his high-priestly intercession takes — holding the disciples through the sifting so that faith, not the pebble of sin, remains.</p>',
        "10": '<p class="christ-allusion">Those who say &quot;disaster shall not overtake or meet us&quot; — the self-exemption from covenant accountability — are the people Paul identifies as saying &quot;Peace and safety!&quot; when sudden destruction comes (1 Thess 5:3). The complacency Amos denounces in 6:1 reaches its theological definition here: it is the denial of one&apos;s own accountability before YHWH. Christ&apos;s parables repeatedly target this exact posture — the foolish virgins who assume they have enough (Matt 25:1-13), the man who builds larger barns (Luke 12:16-21).</p>',
        "12": '<p class="christ-direct">This verse is the pivot of the Jerusalem Council. James cites the LXX of Amos 9:11-12 — &quot;that the remnant of mankind may seek the Lord, and all the Gentiles who are called by my name&quot; (Acts 15:17) — as scriptural warrant for the Gentile mission without circumcision. The MT reads &quot;Edom&quot; where the LXX reads &quot;mankind&quot; (<em>Adam</em>/<em>Edom</em> share consonants). James reads in the LXX text the universal scope of the restored Davidic kingdom: not merely Israel&apos;s dominion over neighboring territories but all nations coming under the name of YHWH through Christ&apos;s resurrection. Amos&apos;s restoration promise becomes the exegetical ground for the Gentile church.</p>',
        "13": '<p class="christ-allusion">The days of superabundant harvest — plowman overtaking reaper, mountains dripping new wine — are anticipated in Christ&apos;s first sign at Cana: six stone water jars of wine, each holding 20-30 gallons, transformed from water (John 2:1-11). The sign is eschatological: the best wine saved for last is the new covenant&apos;s abundance surpassing the old. The quantity and quality of Cana&apos;s wine anticipates the &quot;mountains dripping new wine&quot; of Amos&apos;s restoration — the arriving kingdom announcing itself through the language of eschatological plenty.</p>',
        "14": '<p class="christ-allusion">The restoration of fortunes, the rebuilding of ruined cities, the planting of vineyards — these are the images of full new-creation reversal. Jesus uses vineyard language for the kingdom (Matt 21:33-43) and declares himself the true vine in which all fruitfulness has its source (John 15:1-5). The &quot;planting&quot; in Amos 9:15 finds its christological form in the grafting of Gentiles into Israel&apos;s vine (Rom 11:17-24): the wild branches included in the root and fatness of the cultivated olive tree, sharing in the restored blessing that Amos&apos;s restoration envisions.</p>',
        "15": '<p class="christ-allusion">&quot;I will plant them on their land, and they shall never again be uprooted from the land that I have given them&quot; — the permanence of restored planting — is the OT form of Paul&apos;s declaration that &quot;nothing in all creation will be able to separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus our Lord&quot; (Rom 8:38-39). The never-again-uprooted promise is the eschatological security that Christ secures: &quot;I give them eternal life, and they will never perish, and no one will snatch them out of my hand&quot; (John 10:28). The planting that cannot be uprooted is the life hidden with Christ in God (Col 3:3).</p>'
    }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'amos')
    merge_comm(existing, AMOS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'amos', existing)
    print('Amos 6-9 mkt-christ written.')

